# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] A presidential election was held in Pennsylvania on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1788–89 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Voters chose 10 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania unanimously voted for nonpartisan candidate and commander-in-chief of the Continental Army, George Washington.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] The total vote is composed of 6,718 for Federalist electors, known as the Lancaster Ticket, and 912 for Anti-Federalist electors, known as the Harrisburg Ticket, all of whom were supportive of Washington.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The **1788 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania**, held on September 30, 1788, was the first United States Senate election held in Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States Senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class I seat, while Federalist and American Founding Father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class III seat.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] Upon the expiration of Senator Maclay's term in 1791, the State House of Representatives would not be able to elect a new United States senator due to a dispute regarding the rules and procedures of the election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The seat was finally filled in a 1793 election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election** was the first gubernatorial election after the establishment of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania as a U.S. state.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Mifflin, the incumbent President of the Supreme Executive Council of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania was elected as the first Governor of Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] He defeated Federalist candidate Arthur St.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Clair, former Revolutionary War general and President of the Continental Congress, by a wide margin.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Elections to the United States House of Representatives were held in Pennsylvania on Tuesday, October 11, 1791, for the 2nd Congress.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Six Pro-Administration and two Anti-Administration Representatives had been elected on an at-large basis in the previous election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The elections in Pennsylvania were the last elections held for the 2nd Congress, out of the states that were in the Union at the start of the Congress.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The previous election had been held at-large, but for the 2nd Congress, Pennsylvania divided itself up into 8 districts.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Note: Many of these counties covered much larger areas in 1791 than they do today, having since been divided into smaller counties.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Five incumbents (3 Anti-Administration and 2 Pro-Administration) ran for re-election, four of whom won.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The incumbents George Clymer (P) and Henry Wynkoop (P) of the 2nd district and Thomas Scott (P) of the 8th district did not run for re-election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Muhlenberg switched from Pro-Administration to Anti-Administration.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Four Pro-Administration and four Anti-Administration candidates were elected, a net gain of 2 seats for the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Election data are incomplete for the 1st and 2nd districts and are missing for the 4th and 5th districts.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on October 9, 1792, for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Eight representatives, 4 Pro-Administration and 4 Anti-Administration, had been elected in the previous election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] In the previous election, Pennsylvania had been divided into 8 districts.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Five additional seats had been apportioned to Pennsylvania after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] All 13 seats were elected at-large, an attempt by the Pro-Administration-majority legislature of Pennsylvania to prevent the election of Anti-Administration Representatives.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This backfired and an 8-5 Anti-Administration majority was elected.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was the last year in which Pennsylvania would elect all of its representatives at-large.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] In the following election, Pennsylvania would be divided up into 12 districts (including one plural district).
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] At various times between 1873 and 1945, between 1 and 4 of Pennsylvania's Representatives were elected at-large, with the rest being elected from single-member districts.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] A presidential election was held in Pennsylvania in 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania voters chose 15 members of the Electoral College, each of whom, under the provisions of the Constitution prior to the passage of the Twelfth Amendment, cast two votes for President.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania unanimously voted for nonpartisan candidate and incumbent President George Washington.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] The two best performing electors in Pennsylvania, Joseph Hiester and William Henry, were supported by both parties.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] They received 3,396 and 3,371 votes respectively.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] It is not known which one voted for Clinton.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] The total for Washington only includes the 3,396 number as to not represent Pennsylvanian voters twice in popular vote figures.
[src:1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election/1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **Pennsylvania's 1st congressional district** on October 11, 1808, to fill a vacancy left by the resignation of Joseph Clay (DR) on March 28, 1808.
